@node Entry Paths and Calling Convention
@section Entry Paths and Calling Convention

VibeOS provides two ways for user mode to enter the kernel:

@itemize @bullet
@item @code{int $0x80} through IDT vector 128, and
@item amd64 @code{syscall} through the MSR-programmed fast path.
@end itemize

The main calling convention follows the Linux amd64 syscall ABI:

@itemize @bullet
@item syscall number in @code{rax},
@item arguments in @code{rdi}, @code{rsi}, @code{rdx}, @code{r10},
@code{r8}, and @code{r9}, and
@item return value in @code{rax}.
@end itemize

The dispatcher itself is a large switch over syscall numbers in
@file{kernel/src/syscall.c}.

@node Files and Paths
@section Files, Paths, and Directories

The following file and path calls are recognized:

@multitable @columnfractions .10 .20 .70
@headitem Nr @tab Name @tab Notes
@item 2 @tab @code{open} @tab Implemented as an @code{openat} wrapper using
@code{AT_FDCWD}.
@item 3 @tab @code{close} @tab Closes regular descriptors and pipe endpoints.
@item 4 @tab @code{stat} @tab Linux-compat stat on a followed path.
@item 5 @tab @code{fstat} @tab Stat by descriptor.
@item 6 @tab @code{lstat} @tab Linux-compat stat without following the final
symlink.
@item 8 @tab @code{lseek} @tab Supported for files, directories, and
framebuffers where meaningful.
@item 17 @tab @code{pread64} @tab Position-based reads without updating the
normal file offset.
@item 21 @tab @code{access} @tab Existence-style check built on path lookup.
@item 79 @tab @code{getcwd} @tab Returns the kernel-tracked current directory.
@item 80 @tab @code{chdir} @tab Changes the kernel-tracked current directory.
@item 89 @tab @code{readlink} @tab Implemented through @code{readlinkat}.
@item 217 @tab @code{getdents64} @tab Directory enumeration over the merged
namespace.
@item 257 @tab @code{openat} @tab Main path-open primitive.
@item 262 @tab @code{newfstatat} @tab Followed-path stat.
@item 267 @tab @code{readlinkat} @tab Non-following symlink read.
@item 269 @tab @code{faccessat} @tab Same general existence semantics as
@code{access}.
@item 332 @tab @code{statx} @tab Partial compatibility implementation.
@item 439 @tab @code{faccessat2} @tab Same path existence behavior as the
simpler access helpers.
@end multitable

The namespace is read-only, so these calls let programs inspect and traverse
the tree but not persistently change it.

@node Descriptors and Devices
@section Descriptors, Polling, and Devices

Descriptor and multiplexing calls include:

@multitable @columnfractions .10 .20 .70
@headitem Nr @tab Name @tab Notes
@item 0 @tab @code{read} @tab Supports TTY, framebuffer, pipe, regular-file,
and null descriptors.
@item 1 @tab @code{write} @tab Supports TTY, framebuffer, pipe, and null
descriptors.
@item 7 @tab @code{poll} @tab Busy-wait implementation without a timer source.
@item 16 @tab @code{ioctl} @tab TTY and framebuffer-specific commands.
@item 19 @tab @code{readv} @tab Built on repeated @code{read}.
@item 20 @tab @code{writev} @tab Built on repeated @code{write}.
@item 22 @tab @code{pipe} @tab Equivalent to @code{pipe2} with zero flags.
@item 23 @tab @code{select} @tab Blocking scheduler-aware descriptor
multiplexing.
@item 32 @tab @code{dup} @tab Duplicate descriptor.
@item 33 @tab @code{dup2} @tab Duplicate to an exact descriptor.
@item 40 @tab @code{sendfile} @tab File-to-descriptor copy helper.
@item 72 @tab @code{fcntl} @tab Limited support for duplication and flag
queries or updates.
@item 270 @tab @code{pselect6} @tab Same scan model as @code{select}.
@item 292 @tab @code{dup3} @tab Implemented like exact descriptor duplication.
@item 293 @tab @code{pipe2} @tab Main pipe constructor; flags are currently
restricted.
@end multitable

The kernel understands TTY descriptors, @file{/dev/null}, a framebuffer
descriptor, directories, regular files, and pipes.  That is enough to support a
small shell environment with redirection and pipelines.

